  <TR><TD BGCOLOR="#fff5ba" WIDTH="150"><B>Procedural History</B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD ALIGN="left" WIDTH="150">The petitioners are persons who claim<BR ALIGN='left'/>that the income from the sale of their<BR ALIGN='left'/>stock in the South Texas Rice Warehouse<BR ALIGN='left'/>Company should be taxed solely as a<BR ALIGN='left'/>capital gain. The Tax Court found that a<BR ALIGN='left'/>corporate reorganization had taken place<BR ALIGN='left'/>and held that at least part of<BR ALIGN='left'/>petitioners&#x27; income should be taxed as a<BR ALIGN='left'/>dividend constituting ordinary<BR ALIGN='left'/>income.[1] The government took a cross<BR ALIGN='left'/>appeal 877*877 contending that the Tax<BR ALIGN='left'/>Court should have held that a greater<BR ALIGN='left'/>portion of petitioners&#x27; income was<BR ALIGN='left'/>ordinary income.</TD></TR>
